  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Lecce who spent most of her life in a small Italian town, I've watched generations of young people come and go, and I can tell you that the gender gap in science isn't just a statistic—it's a quiet, persistent shadow that affects how children see their potential. Growing up in a place where science was often taught through practical experiments in the schoolyard, I remember my own curiosity being encouraged by my parents, who had modest educations but instilled in me the value of hands-on learning. Today, though, I see fewer girls pursuing STEM fields, not because they lack interest, but because of subtle barriers that start in childhood. For example, when I was younger, I’d often hear boys talking about building robots or coding while girls were encouraged to focus on art or cooking. That cultural shift, even if unintentional, shapes what children believe they can achieve. Addressing this gap requires more than just policies—it needs community involvement, mentors, and a shift in how we present science as something for everyone. In my town, we’ve started small by hosting workshops where girls can explore engineering through simple projects, like building bridges with recycled materials. I believe it’s time to stop seeing science as a 'male' domain and start seeing it as a place where every child, regardless of gender, can thrive. After all, creativity and curiosity are universal, and science should reflect that.",
